US MARKET WRAP 30 Jan 2019: Dovish Fed says it could tweak balance sheet

* SNAP SHOT: equities up, dollar down, treasuries up, crude up

* REAR VIEW: Fed holds rates and shows openness to balance sheet tweaks, ADP nonfarm payrolls beats, Apple (AAPL) earnings beat, crude EIA inventories smaller than expected build, EU stands ground

* AHEAD: Chinese NBS Manufacturing PMI, German Retail Sales & Unemployment Change, French Preliminary CPI, Italian Preliminary GDP, EZ Preliminary GDP (Flash) & Unemployment Rate, Canadian GDP, ECB’s Coeure, Mersch & Weidmann Speaking

 

* FOMC: Heading into the FOMC’s rate decision and statement, the market was looking for an update on the balance sheet, whether the Fed would maintain a “gradual” pace of rate hikes, whether it judges the balance of risks as “roughly balanced” and whether it revises its assessment of the economy. All of those factors saw dovish tweaks in the latest statement: on the balance sheet, the FOMC indicated that it was prepared to adjust the pace of the balance sheet run-off, it dumped language on “gradual” rate hikes, adding in that the Committee will be “patient” on future hikes. The language around “roughly balanced” risks was also dumped, and it downgraded its view of the economy slightly, now characterising it as “solid” from “strong”. The Fed also changed its view on inflation, which it now sees as “muted”. There were some fears among traders that the Fed might not be as dovish as hoped for; that fear was jettisoned with the release of the statement, and the dovish Fed was risk assets bounce higher. In the press conference, Chair Powell sounded upbeat on the economy, reiterating his now familiar message of data-dependence and patience. He did note cross-current headwinds from the slowdown in Chinese and European growth. On rates, Powell said the case for raising rates has weakened somewhat. On the balance sheet, Powell said the policy will be driven by reserve demand, which he suggested was higher than it was a year ago. He also suggested that it was still not the Fed's primary tool of normalisation, that remains rates, though the balance sheet could be used if required (he later said that in a future downturn, the balance sheet would be used to stimulate the economy, but after using rates). He was quizzed about the ideal size of the balance sheet, though he dismissed the question, suggesting the size will be whatever is most efficient to implement the Fed's policy. Powell said rates were now in the range of estimates of neutral; previously he had seen them in the bottom end of the range of the estimates neutral. On the government shutdown, Powell said that it would leave an "imprint" on Q1 growth, though much of that would be made up in the Q2. On trade talks, Powell said that drawn out negotiations could weigh on business confidence.

* ADP reported 213k nonfarm payrolls additions, beating expectations of 178k, which Moody’s Zandi analysed as evidence of the “job market weather[ing] the government shutdown well. Despite the severe disruptions, businesses continued to add aggressively to their payrolls”. Analysts at Pantheon digested this print as “inevitable” and a “healthy-looking gain”. They did note, however that ADP likely overstates NFP’s print as ADP is generated by “a model which incorporates lagged official data”. Pantheon added that they “can’t say for sure how big this effect was, because ADP does not release its model”, and given the small error in their ADP forecast (220k) they have left their 180k prediction for NFP unchanged as “labour demand remains extremely strong, despite the pressure on the manufacturing sector from China’s slowdown and the trade war; manufacturing accounts for only 8.4% of U.S. payrolls.”

* Trade: Limited updates on trade were heard today other than Nikkei reporting that the US-China trade talks began with a focus on financial liberalisation.

* BREXIT: Following UK Parliament’s vote for the Brady amendment yesterday, giving PM May the mandate to reopen the withdrawal agreement with the EU, the responses from the EU have been rather cut-throat. EU Council President Tusk, Commission President Juncker and other EU officials all reiterated their stance that the WA is not to be reopened or renegotiated, with the EU government seeing the likelihood of an extension “ever more likely”. In the UK, May met with the opposition leader Corbyn where they reportedly had a “detailed” conversation regarding the customs union.

* WTI (H9) FUTURES SETTLE USD 0.96 HIGHER AT USD 54.23/BBL, BRENT (H9) FUTURES SETTLE USD 0.33 HIGHER AT USD 61.65/BBL. Oil prices were higher on Wednesday amid ongoing threat of further US sanctions on Venezuela as well as oil output and exports cuts eyed by Saudi Arabia next month.  Citi notes “the market also seems to have accepted the idea that an increase in US petroleum inventories for last week wasn’t enough to undercut support” as the EIA crude stocks reported a smaller than expected build, confirming the API report last night. In terms of news flow, Russian Energy Minister Novak stated that there are no plans for an extra-ordinary meeting for a global oil output cut deal over Venezuela while noting that Russian oil output will decline by 50k BPD in Jan vs. October 2018 levels, and will try to cut oil production by around 50k BPD in February. Also, refinery disruptions have added to the bullish sentiment; Citgo has curbed production at its 167k BPD Lemont, Illinois refinery due to extreme weather.

* SPX +1.56% at 2681, NASDAQ +2.64% at 6808, DJI +1.77% at 25014. SECTORS: Energy +1.35%, Materials +1.05%, Industrials +1.56%, Cons Discretionary +2.17%, Cons Staples +0.74%, Healthcare +1.37%, Financials +0.47%, Tech +3.03%, Telecoms +1.22%, Utilities +0.65%.

Alibaba (BABA) opened in the green after beating EPS estimates and citing little effect from trade tensions on the co. Other notable companies reporting today were Boeing (BA), General Dynamics (GD), Stryker (SYK) and Royal Caribbean Cruises (RCL) who all beat on EPS and revenue estimates, seeing them outperform on the open. Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) surged after its earnings, where it missed on revenue estimates but analysts attributing the miss not as gloomy as competitor NVIDIA (NVDA) had previously painted for the semiconductor space. McDonalds (MCD) traded higher on the open after strong EPS and comparable sales but pared back gains later after citing struggles in the US in its conference call. Amgen (AMGN) underperformed on the back of lowering its 2019 guidance. Israel-based Mellanox (MLNX) outperformed as Intel (INTC) bid USD 5.5bln-6bln for the co. in a cash and stock deal. Citigroup (C) found relief following regulators dropping plans of fining the bank for discriminatory mortgage lending. General Electric (GE) traded higher after announcing it was combining renewable and grid assets into one unit as well as seeing bidding interest for its Capital Aviation Services. Allergan (AGN) and Whirlpool (WHR) underperformed following downgrades at Morgan Stanley and RBC Capital respectively. Take-Two Interactive (TTWO) benefitted from a New Buy initiation at Goldman.

* US T-NOTE FUTURES (H9) SETTLED 7 TICKS HIGHER AT 122-00. Treasury futures drifted lower in earlier trade into the US equity open - exacerbated by a stronger than expected ADP report at 213K – before the trading range bound until the FOMC decision. The Fed took a dovish stance, removing references to gradual rate hikes and also mentioned its openness to tweaking the balance sheet runoff, as of such, treasuries caught a large bid with the front end leading causing steepening across the curve; the 2/30 seeing the greatest steepening at c.7bps. Elsewhere, the US Treasury announced next week it will sell USD 38bln in 3yr, USD 27bln in 10yr and USD 19bln in 30yr; to raise USD 29.9bln in new cash; as expected.

* USD:  On the much awaited FOMC rate decision, the Dollar weakened and printed fresh lows at 95.246 amid dovish tweaks in the latest FOMC statement and Fed’s Powell stance shifting more dovish; at the press conference he stressed data-dependency and suggested that rates are now in the range of estimates of neutral. The DXY consolidated just off session lows at around 95.380.

* AUD, CAD: The Aussie built build on gains above 0.7250 vs its US rival falling victim of USD weakness. The Cad has not really been ruffled by benign Canadian average weekly earnings but struggles towards 1.3200.

* NOK: Also benefiting from the ongoing rebound in crude, but also further weakness or underperformance in the SEK following deteriorations in Swedish business and consumer sentiment. Eur/Nok now down through 9.7000, and sub-9.6900 at one stage vs Eur/Sek close to 10.4000 at the high.

* GBP: Back to pretty flat on the day, but still holding above initial post-UK Parliamentary Brexit vote lows as Cable continues to derive tech support above its 200 DMA (1.3055) and Eur/Gbp is capped ahead of 0.8750. Next up for the Pound, a call between PM May and EC’s Tusk in wake of last night’s Brady amendment approval that gives her the mandate to go back to Brussels and attempt to replace the Irish backstop with some kind of alternative.

* JPY/CHF: Marked underperformers as the Jpy finally broke down and out of its recent range base of 109.50, though a couple of HMAs on its way to 109.73, while the Franc weakened further before finding some underlying bids/support near parity.

* EUR: The single currency has topped out around 1.1450 vs the Dollar again, and perhaps belatedly in response to more soft Eurozone macro indicators in the form or German CPI and a pronounced drop in French household spending. Sitting above 1.1480 in post-FOMC trade.

Daily FX Wrap: DXY eyeing 96.000 into the Fed, Gbp awaiting Brexit call
content:
USD

The Dollar is inching higher ahead of the 1st FOMC policy meeting of 2019, and a stronger than expected ADP survey as a proxy for NFP may have been a catalyst. However, we suspect a combination of short covering and hedging against a less dovish Fed than many anticipate or are just hoping for. The DXY has pared losses from just under 95.700 to almost 96.000, but not quite and looking for further prompts from the FOMC.

AUD/CAD

The Aussie is off best levels having failed to build on gains above 0.7200 vs its US rival and seriously challenge a near term upside chart level just beyond the big figure (0.7207), but remains ahead in the G10 ranks, albeit closely followed and almost eclipsed by the Loonie. The catalysts, firmer than forecast Q4 Australian CPI data overnight, higher iron ore and oil prices. Note, the Cad has not really been ruffled by benign Canadian average weekly earnings as it extends recovery gains towards 1.3200.

NOK

Also benefiting from the ongoing rebound in crude, but also further weakness or underperformance in the SEK following deteriorations in Swedish business and consumer sentiment. Eur/Nok now down through 9.7000, and sub-9.6900 at one stage vs Eur/Sek close to 10.4000 at the high.

GBP  

Back to pretty flat on the day, but still holding above initial post-UK Parliamentary Brexit vote lows as Cable continues to derive tech support above its 200 DMA (1.3055) and Eur/Gbp is capped ahead of 0.8750. Next up for the Pound, a call between PM May and EC’s Tusk in wake of last night’s Brady amendment approval that gives her the mandate to go back to Brussels and attempt to replace the Irish backstop with some kind of alternative.

JPY/CHF

Marked underperformers as the Jpy finally broke down and out of its recent range base of 109.50, though a couple of HMAs on its way to 109.73, while the Franc weakened further before finding some underlying bids/support near parity.

EUR

The single currency has topped out around 1.1450 vs the Dollar again, and perhaps belatedly in response to more soft Eurozone macro indicators in the form or German CPI and a pronounced drop in French household spending.

EM

Contrasting fortunes for the Lira and Peso, as hawkish rhetoric from the CBRT supported the Try’s rebound from 5.3200+ vs the Usd, but the Mxn weakened from circa 19.0000 to 19.2100 in wake of a Mexican GDP miss and the earlier Pemex credit downgrade.

content: It may well be too premature to suggest, but bond and currency markets could now essentially be full wind down mode ahead of the Fed. Indeed, it’s largely been a grind for a while now, with only minor blips and price deviations around the benign German CPI, ADP beat and less so following the US Treasury’s Quarterly Refunding announcement. However, Bunds and Gilts have subsequently nudged back up towards best levels within their 165.26-164.99 and 123.32-07 Eurex and Liffe parameters, while the Usd is firming up to fresh highs for the day – DXY only a whisker away from 96.000 – perhaps on the premise that the FOMC may not prove as dovish as many are anticipating.

Bunds and Gilts are both back on an even keel after forging fresh intraday lows at 164.99 and 123.07 respectively earlier, and the 2 EU benchmarks now look set to bide time until US participants arrive for FOMC day. COMMODITIES

Follows sanctions announced on Monday which aim to stop the proceeds from PDVSA’s crude exports of around 500,00 BPD to the US.

Gold (+0.1%) is trading in the middle of its USD 6/oz range, on a steady dollar ahead of today’s FOMC decision. Elsewhere, Vale’s CEO announced they will take up to 10% of the Co’s output offline to decommission 10 dams following Friday’s dam burst.

  • Asian stocks traded indecisively following better than expected Apple results and ahead of US-China trade talks
  • UK lawmakers accepted Brady's amendment for the backstop to be replaced with an alternative arrangement and accepted Spelman's amendment that expressed objection to a no-deal Brexit

ASIA-PAC

Asian stocks traded indecisively with the region tentative heading into this week’s key risk events and as participants also digested better than expected Apple results, which only provided brief support to US equity futures after-hours. ASX 200 (+0.1%) and Nikkei 225 (-0.4%) were both subdued although strength across commodities just about kept the Australian benchmark afloat, while Tokyo stocks were weighed by currency effects and uninspiring corporate updates. Elsewhere, Hang Seng (-0.1%) and Shanghai Comp. (-0.3%) declined at the open amid broad weakness in the region and with China Life Insurance shares heavily pressured after it flagged a 50%-70% drop in FY net, although Chinese markets then rebounded off lows amid a non-committal tone ahead of the looming US-China trade talks and after the PBoC injected liquidity for the 1st time in 8 days. Finally, 10yr JGBs were uneventful with prices stuck to within this week’s tight range amid the indecision seen across the region and with an unchanged BoJ Rinban announcement largely ignored.

China is expected to present a roadmap on structural reforms to US during this week’s meetings in Washington. (Nikkei)


UK/EU

UK lawmakers accepted Brady's amendment (N) by 317 to 301 votes which requires the backstop to be replaced with alternative arrangement, while lawmakers also accepted Spelman's amendment (I) by 318 to 310 votes which expresses MP objection to a no-deal Brexit by stating that the House of Commons "rejects the United Kingdom leaving the European Union without a Withdrawal Agreement and a Framework for the Future Relationship". However, Parliament rejected the other 5 amendments which were voted on including those which involve delaying the Brexit date. (Newswires)

UK PM May said the majority of members have said they will support a deal with changes to the backstop and that she will seek legally binding changes to the WA. (Newswires) Following the vote, opposition leader Corbyn has finally agreed to meet with UK PM May. (Newswires)

French President Macron’s office said that the divorce deal and backstop is not up for renegotiation and that France will push ahead with preparations for a no-deal scenario, while an EU spokesperson also reiterated Brexit deal and backstop will not be renegotiated but added that the EU is ready to consider a Brexit delay. (Newswires)

Austrian Cabinet will name Robert Holzmann as future Governor of Austrian National Bank on Wednesday who will succeed ECB's Nowotny when his term expires at the end of August, according to government sources. (Newswires)

Italian Deputy PM Salvini is reportedly feeling the pressure to call for an early election this year amid tensions with the 5SM. (Newswires)

US Trade Representative Lighthizer said the US will aggressively fight the EU on olive tariffs. (Newswires)


FX

In FX markets, the greenback remained uneventful with the DXY kept sideways so far this week ahead of the upcoming FOMC meeting, while major counterpart EUR/USD was also rangebound at the 1.1400 handle. GBP/USD attempted to nurse some of the losses seen following the voting in Parliament, where UK lawmakers accepted Brady's amendment for the backstop to be replaced with an alternative arrangement, and accepted Spelman's amendment that expressed objection to a no-deal Brexit. This effectively weighed on the GBP/USD considering the EU have remained adamant the withdrawal agreement or backstop was not up for renegotiation, while lawmakers also rejected the 5 other amendments including those involving delaying the Brexit date. Elsewhere, high-beta currencies were eventually supported by an intraday recovery in sentiment with AUD/USD the outperformer after firmer than expected CPI data which pushed the pair within a whisker of the 0.7200 handle and lifted AUD/NZD to above 1.0500, while USD/JPY was constrained by the indecisive risk appetite and CNY continued its recent strengthening trend after another firmer fix by the PBoC.

Australian CPI (Q4) Y/Y 1.8% vs. Exp. 1.7% (Prev. 1.9%)


COMMODITIES

Commodities marginally extended on recent gains with WTI crude futures above the USD 53.00/bbl amid supply concerns after further sanction threats by the US on Venezuela and with Saudi Arabia also planning further output cuts next month, while the latest API inventory report showed headline crude stockpiles at smaller than expected build. Elsewhere, gold continued to edge higher amid a lacklustre greenback, copper conformed to the upside seen across the complex and Dalian iron ore futures surged to hit limit up in early trade after Vale announced to cut production in the wake of the dam collapse in Brazil.

US API Weekly Crude Stocks (25 Jan) +2.098mln vs. Exp. +3.2mln (prev. +6.55mln). (Newswires)

Saudi Arabia is planning on further cuts to oil production and exports next month, while it believes US can solve its Venezuela oil shortage problem with SPR releases. (WSJ)

US

Treasuries pushed higher following the auction and an overhang of risk factors such as the evolving Brexit scenario, caution ahead of key China trade talks and worries about the shutdown’s impact. The majority of today’s action was seen in the belly of the curve where the 5-year yield fell by 3.1bps, 7-year fell 3.5bps and 10-year fell 3.2bps; the 2-year and 30-year both fell by a more muted c. 2bps. The 5s30s and 10s30s spreads widened by c. 1bps, whereas we saw flattening at the front to belly of the curve. The US Treasury sold USD 32bln of 7-year notes today in what could be considered an average auction, tailing by 0.3bps at a high yield of 2.625%, the lowest since January 2018. Indirect bidders took below the six-week auction average, however, so did dealer bidders and direct bidders took 24.9%, well above the 15.2% average. US T-note futures (H9) settled 9 ticks higher at 121-25.
